ns the bit index is `row * 16 + col`.\\n2. **Toroidal Topology**: To implement the wrap-around effect, for any cell at `(r, c)`, the neighbors are `((r-1+16)%16, (c-1+16)%16)`, `((r-1+16)%16, c)`, etc. In RTL, this can be handled by indexing using modulo arithmetic or by shifting.\\n3. **Game Logic**: \\n   - Count neighbors for each cell. \\n   - If neighbors == 3, next state = 1.\\n   - If neighbors == 2, next state = current state.\\n   - Otherwise (0, 1, or 4+), next state = 0.\\n4. **Implementation Strategy**: \\n   - Use a 2D array (or logic array) to represent the grid for easier indexing during the combinational calculation.\\n   - Calculate the next state for all 256 cells in a combinational block.\\n   - Use a sequential block to update the state on the positive edge of the clock, handling the `load` signal.\\n5. **Syntax Advice**: \\n   - Use `always @(*)` for combinational logic to avoid sensitivity list errors.\\n   - Use `always @(posedge clk)` for sequential logic.\\n   - When indexing 2D grids, ensure indices are within [0:15].\\n   - Use the `+:` bit-slicing operator for clarity when working with the 256-bit vector.",\n    "module": "module TopModule(\\n    input  logic       clk,\\n    input  logic       load,\\n    input  logic [255:0] data,\\n    output logic [255:0] q\\n);\\n\\n    logic [255:0] q_next;\\n    logic [15:0]  grid [0:15];\\n    logic [15:0]  next_grid [0:15];\\n    int           neighbor_count;\\n    int           r, c, dr, dc;\\n\\n    // Convert flat vector to 2D grid for easier neighbor calculation\\n    always @(*) begin\\n        for (int i = 0; i < 16; i++) begin\\n            grid[i] = q[i*16 +: 16];\\n        end\\n    end\\n\\n    // Combinational logic for the next state\\n    always @(*) begin\\n        // Initialize next_grid with 0\\n        for (int i = 0; i < 16; i++) begin\\n            next_grid[i] = 16\'b0;\\n        end\\n\\n        for (r = 0; r < 16; r = r + 1) begin\\n            for (c = 0; c < 16; c = c + 1)